Question 4

Rather than geom_boxplot, add geom_jitter(height = 0.15) to create a plot with displ on the x axis and drv on the y axis. Add summaries for both mean (blue) and median (red).

mpg <- as.data.frame(mpg)
head(mpg)
##   manufacturer model displ year cyl      trans drv cty hwy fl   class
## 1         audi    a4   1.8 1999   4   auto(l5)   f  18  29  p compact
## 2         audi    a4   1.8 1999   4 manual(m5)   f  21  29  p compact
## 3         audi    a4   2.0 2008   4 manual(m6)   f  20  31  p compact
## 4         audi    a4   2.0 2008   4   auto(av)   f  21  30  p compact
## 5         audi    a4   2.8 1999   6   auto(l5)   f  16  26  p compact
## 6         audi    a4   2.8 1999   6 manual(m5)   f  18  26  p compact
ggplot(mpg, aes(hwy, class)) + 
  geom_jitter(height = 0.15) +
  stat_summary(geom = "point", fun = "mean", color = "green", size = 2) +
  stat_summary(geom = "point", fun = "median", color = "red", size = 2)

Question 5

Notice that in this section, we made several calls to layers that included arguments specifying visual aspects of the data (stat_summary(…, color = ‘red’, size = 2) and geom_jitter(height = 0.15)) without using the aes() function. Why did this still work? What impact did it have on the plots that were created?

This works because the aes() function is modifying the descriptive data of the graph as opposed to describing the data itself. The stat_summary function instead is adding to the graph, and the size and color are specific to that function. These params affect the stat summary and how easy it is to comprehend.

It was not running because the aes() function needs to be nested in ggplot() when there are multiple layers/concatenations using the + function.

Question 7

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color = drv))

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy, color = drv)) + 
  geom_point()

The plots are visually identical. The only difference is in the nesting of the aes() function, which would be problematic if there were more layers in the second function.

## Plot 1
ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color = drv)) + 
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

## Plot 2
ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy, color = drv)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

Plot 2 applies aes(displ, hwy, color = drv) to all three of the color mapped functions, which makes the data much more visually cluttered and challenging to understand.

Question 8

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy, color = factor(cyl))) +
  geom_point()

class(mpg$cyl) = "integer" Because integers are a continuous variable, the legend and color coding is displayed in a gradient, with darker values representing lower cyl values.

Question 9

This changes the structure of the color coding for cyl to be discrete instead of continuous. In this case, we don’t think that this is necessarily a good change, as a continuous variable would be a better representation of the data type.

Question 10

  geom_boxplot(alpha = 1)

When we first ran it, we had issues with the coloring. We solved this by converting the year into a factor, according to the warning that R gave us! Great!

Question 11

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) +
  geom_point(color = "blue")

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = "blue"))

The first plot has blue points because the color arg modifies the points. However, in the second example the aes() function nested in the point generation is an addition layer, and that layer only has the information of color = "blue", without any direction for what is supposed to be blue. Therefore it creates a key displaying this information to the best of the software’s abilities.
